design:
Runtime API (Session-owned, lazy Agent):

  pub struct Runtime {
      profile_name: String,
      store_path: PathBuf,
      figment: Figment,
      session: CredentialSession,   // owns store (Arc<AppPasswordStore>) + resolver
  }

  impl Runtime {
      // Boot the active profile's fjall store + CredentialSession. Resume-only:
      // never prompts, never calls createSession. Returns Ok even on an empty
      // store (session state is LoginRequired until a command needs auth).
      pub async fn from_profile(figment: Figment, profile: Option<&str>) -> Result<Runtime>;

      // Lazily resume -> authenticated jacquard Agent. Errors (or returns a typed
      // LoginRequired) when the store has no live session for this profile.
      pub async fn agent(&self) -> Result<Agent>;

      pub fn session(&self) -> &CredentialSession;
      pub fn profile_name(&self) -> &str;
      pub fn store_path(&self) -> &Path;
  }

Store-path resolution moves here verbatim from login_real:
  active.store_path OR config_dir/store/<profile>.db (mkdir -p parent).

What MOVES into tassle-app:
  - store open (TursoRepository::open_local -> AppPasswordStore -> Arc)
  - JacquardResolver + CredentialSession::new
  - store_path resolution + session_status's store re-open (fold into Runtime)

What STAYS in tassle-cli:
  - interactive password prompt (rpassword) + TASSLE_PASSWORD env fallback
  - login_from_challenge call (login is a CLI action; Runtime is resume-only)
  - writing the non-secret profile fragment (did/handle/pds/session_id)
  - clap arg types, OutputFormat / JSON printing

Feature gating: crate exposes Runtime behind `auth-store`; unauthenticated
commands (repo/self_record) keep BasicClient and don't need a Runtime yet.
